710296f.text:
Ninth Avenue, at Gansevoort Street, showing the curve in the first "El" line at this point. Emerging out of Greenwich Street, it continues northward to 29th Street. The view in this instance is southwestward silhouetting the steel framework against the limited west frontage lying between Gansevoort and Little West 12th Street. The last thoroughfare is on the right. Note the flag
poles at the corners of same.
For additional views of this early phase of the Charles C. Harvey line, see Ninth Avenue at 29th Street, and
Greenwich Street at Dey Street.
1867-8
Gift of Major Quinn
Neg. No.14

710297f.text:
Ninth Avenue, at Gansevoort Street, showing the "El" curve at this point after its emergence out of Greenwich Street. The photographer is viewing southward from a point slightly above Little West 12th Street. The latter appears at the right. Note the drum like apparatus recuired to continue the wire cable. This method of locomotion was replaced with small steam
locomotives.
1867-8
Gift of Major Quinn
Neg. No.8

719986f-b.text:
Gansevoort Street, south side, west from Greenwich Street (9th Avenue elevated line thereon) showing a portion of the wholesale produce market that is located in this area. To the left are buildings on the west side of Greenwich Street extending south from Gansevoort to Horatio Streets. The empty lot seen in the foreground is at the
S.E. corner of this point.
No. 2 and 3 show only the Gansevoort Street buildings. On the right of the former is the Manhattan Refrigerating Co. plant on
Washington Street.
August 11, 1938.
Views 1,2 and 3.
P. L. Sperr
